\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 I don\rquote 
t understand about the boundary between psychology and sociology, or psychology and anthropology.  I think Pitt-Rivers somewhere says that the question of motive in the social action always escapes us because you can\rquote 
t access it reliably. You can ask people what they\rquote re doing, or what they think they\rquote re doing, or what they\rquote re planning, but you can\rquote t rely on self-reporting, but there\rquote s nothing else.  So it seems to me that w
hen you are doing any kind of qualitative work that isn\rquote t tied up with social psychology and lab experiments, you\rquote re forced into interpretative inferences about what people are doing, and what they\rquote 
re trying to do, and what they mean by it. And like any other social actor, you form estimates of reliability or unreliability, just as historians do when they\rquote re looking at sources. They say, \'93This guy sailed all around the world.  He\rquote 
s extremely sloppy, his facts are often wildly \'85\'94, or they say, \'93He\rquote s \'85 he\rquote s a terribly good reporter, and whenever you can check on something he says, you find it\rquote s pretty close to it\'94.  So there\rquote 
s an interpreting the reliability of your informants}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3486225\charrsid14965953 , and how thoughtful they are.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 So I\rquote ve always worked on the assumption that we can\rquote t
 be rigorous, in qualitative work, in the end, you make inferential judgements.  You leap gaps.  And in a rigorous experimental sense, there will be black boxes or holes in the evidence.  Yeah?  And I\rquote 
m prepared to go ahead on that basis, knowing that economists and social psychologists would be quite unhappy with the way anthropologists characteristically do things.  But I think I don\rquote t care!  (LAUGHS)  I mean, let them do their stuff, and let
\rquote s see what co}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3486225\charrsid14965953 mes out at the end of the day.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 I have a passage here on my objections to all disciplinary imperialisms.  I don\rquote t believe that anthropology is, in any sense, a superior social science, I think it\rquote 
s one among equals, and we all contribute according to our competencies, and I would have been just as happy to be, I think, if I\rquote 
d got the talent for it, and with hindsight, I would have been perfectly happy to have been an epidemiologist or a demographer, which are both numerical, non-qualitative, because I think that the stuff they come up with is terribly important. So I don
\rquote t feel, \'93Oh, it\rquote s got to be qualitative research or nothing\'94.  I feel if I\rquote d been a bit better at \lquote O\rquote  Level maths, and I\rquote 
