{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 All right.  Well, I was dropping out of the BBC, if you see what I mean.  And having been told I couldn\rquote 
t have a half day off - there was a bad year in which my mother died while I was on an assignment in America.  The doctors had said they thought she had a year to live, and this turned out to be less than a month.  Because, your mother\rquote 
s got cancer.  She\rquote s in hospital.  Do you stop your normal professional life, or what do you do?  So you ask the doctors, \'93How long has she got?\'94  And this sort of cancer, nobody thought it was curable.  \'93How long has she got?\'94
  And they said, \'93Oh, perhaps a year\'94.  So you hear \'93the year\'94, you don\rquote t hear the \'93perhaps\'94.  So I set off for the States on an assignment, did three or four weeks, doing three films, one in Bo
ston, one in Chicago, and then the phone rang. It was the big boss, and he said, \'93I\rquote m sorry to tell you your mother died last night\'94.  So when I got back, my immediate boss said to me, \'93I sent you to do three stories, and you\rquote 
ve only done two\'94.  I said, \'93Well, I went down to Houston, and I couldn\rquote t see what to do\'94.  And, of course, I couldn\rquote t, there was a story to be done, but I was already rather tense from the first two, and tired, and I didn\rquote 
