\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 
Relatively brief, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 Yes.  He\rquote 
s born in a village in Cyprus about 1905.  Son of the village priest.  First one to get to secondary school.  Goes on to the Pan-Cyprian Gymnasium, qualifies as a primary school teacher.  Starts teaching.  Joins the Communist Party \endash 
 member number 5 or 6 or 7, I can\rquote t remember \endash  he joins very early, the first Communist Party in Cyprus under the influence of a m}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2693190\charrsid14965953 
ainland Greek agitator or \endash  \lquote agitator\rquote  is the wrong word \endash  \lquote militant\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 
.  Various adventures in Cyprus, about which I can supply you with written documentation.  I\rquote ve written an article about my father and the Communist Party, all right?  And he finally l
eaves the island in 1930, after trouble with his brother-in-law, over not bringing the right doctor, and his sister dying in childbirth.  So he\rquote s blamed for that by his dead sister\rquote s husband.  And he\rquote 
s in trouble with the Church for being in the Communist Party and defending a Communist poet that the Church had been attacking.  So he leaves Cyprus in a burst of emotion, arrives in London.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 
Wait a minute, though!  
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 
You asked about my father!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 
No, I know!  But what you didn\rquote t say, which you say in the written version, is that he made this repentance to the Church. When you wrote it, you said it was because of that humiliation that he decided to leave.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 
Yeah.  Look, he reckoned - I have sent you the long article about him being tried by the Church?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 
Oh well, certainly an article, whether it\rquote s that one, I don\rquote t know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 
Does it include his letter defending the Communist poet?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 
All right.  Well, okay, what seems to be clear is that at this trial \endash  the Church organised some kind of a hearing of him and three other Communist schoolteachers, of whom one was the poet [Tefcros] Anthias, who didn\rquote 
t go to the hearing, told them to get lost! (LAUGHS)  And my father, being a good boy, turned up at the h
earing, along with a couple of others, and the Church demanded to know whether they were Christians or not, which, in Greek, in the last shadow of the Ottoman Empire, more or less carries the implication of, \'93
Are you ethnic Greek Cypriots, or something else?\'94  And to deny being a Christian is to deny membership in the Orthodox millet [an ethno-religious category of government of Orthodox Christians], so there\rquote 
s a confusion. The Communist Party says it\rquote s formally atheistic \endash  God doesn\rquote t exist \endash  but my father
, who writes about God in a complex kind of way that God may not have forgotten the world, but the Church has taken God away from people, and the working-class movement can bring human beings back into a proper \'85
 I mean, if there is a God, God has to help the working-class, because the Church ain\rquote t doing nothing for it.  So he has not, in writing, denied the existence of God, even though the Communist Party does. So my father and the others said, \'93
Yes, we are Christians\'94, and the Church\rquote s view was sort of, \'93Gotcha!  Because your Party says, \lquote God doesn\rquote t exist\rquote  so you\rquote ve got to write a repudiation of something.  You either write a repudiation of your atheism
\'94, or in my father\rquote s case, \'93a repudiation of your defence of Anthias\'94.  Now, I\rquote m not sure which of those he did.  Maybe both.  But whatever he did \endash  and this is a tradition in anti-Communist Movements in Greece and Cyprus 
\endash  that you get people to write a kind of confession of their error, which is exactly what the Communist Party does with people as well, so my father then feels he\rquote s betrayed the Party, he\rquote 
s failed to uphold the ideals.  I imagine that he was in a state of some intellectual, cognitive and moral confusion about how you answer this trick question \endash  \'93Are you a Christian?\'94 It\rquote s very difficult to
 deny the existence of God in Greek culture, Greek village culture.  It\rquote s just the same as the refusal in Islam.  It\rquote s a monstrous step to take.  Only a very refined urban intellectual who\rquote 
d kind of thought the whole thing through, would formally say, \'93I am an atheist. God does not exist\'94.  It\rquote s safe to be anti-clerical, but you can\rquote t be anti-God.  All right?  I think it works like that!  
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 
So he was humiliated though, was he?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 
He was humiliated by two failures \endash  a personal failure in the village, and a political failure in the eyes of his comrades.  I mean, my father was never a very stalwart member of the CP.  He tried to get out almost as soon as he\rquote 
d joined, but was persuaded to brace up and -  do you want that story?  (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 Well, 
I think you mentioned there were rumours that he belonged to a Communist cell in Soho.
\par  
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 Oh, it\rquote 
s not only rumours!  The fact that he was being followed by MI5 is a matter of public record.  One Colonial civil servant wrote to somebody in Whitehall, saying, \'93
In response to your inquiries, this man is the leader of we think a dangerous group who meet at such and such a caf\'e9 in Soho\'94. Years later, I said to my father, \'93Well, were you the leader of a dangerous group?  And were you receiving any Russian 
help?  Any money coming across?\'94 (LAUGHS)  \'93Dear God, no, nothing at all!  No!\'94  (LAUGHS)  He made this very Greek gesture of nullity, which is nothing, you bite your thumb and flick it away from your teeth. No, no, nothing, they weren\rquote 
t getting a penny!  (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 
And what did he work as?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 He didn\rquote 
t!  That\rquote s the whole trouble with my father in London in the 1930s.  He washed dishes occasionally, but he was unemployed for most of the thirties. He became a gambler on Greyhounds over in Catford a
nd Peckham. There was a dog track, and he borrowed money off everybody in sight, and as far as I can see, he must have borrowed off my mother when they went out on dates, he never had a penny.  And her brothers, who were decent, working-class Londoners, w
ho were always employed, and fought/boxed for money, and all kinds of stuff. They didn\rquote t stand around. [They] were contemptuous of him for this.  I mean, the British wouldn\rquote t recognise his teaching qualification.  Do you know the book, }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 Small Island?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 Yes.
