ve had plenty of time to think and look around, and there\rquote s th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13792356\charrsid14965953 ese funny little people called \lquote Cypriots\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 
 who are sort of  half my size, and little old ladies are vomiting in corners, and the men are dressed in funny clothes. And when we get off the coast of Cyprus, about five in the morning, you sail past Paphos, and I think it\rquote s September, it
\rquote s either August or September, so it\rquote s hot and dry, and I look out at the coast, and it just looks like a desert from the sea.  Everything\rquote s parched and bleached, and because I knew nothing about the Med, or its sea
sons or anything about it \endash  I hadn\rquote t been reading anthropology and Mediterranean Studies and so on, I\rquote d just had my head in movies, movies, movies for five years \endash  and now I\rquote 
m on this boat, see this coast, and it just looks like a wasteland!  And I think, \'93This is a desert.  How can people live there?  I mean, what do they }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
