\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 
Well, they feast me.  I mean, the food is amazing, delicious, generous, unfamiliar. Lots of strong drink served with it.  Lots of toasting.  It\rquote s very decorous.  You don\rquote 
t drink at will in Cyprus, you drink in rounds and toasts.  So if I raise my glass, everybody raises their glass.  Or if they raise their glass, I must raise my glass.  But it\rquote 
s not like drinking in an English pub where I pick up my glass when I feel like it.  So there\rquote s all that ceremonial stuff.  There\rquote s speeches - welcome, speeches of welcome \endash  and I have to respond, so I make a speech
 about having had to sort of carry my father\rquote 
s name as a child, and it not making any sense to me, and having suffered in some small way for it, it now all suddenly seems worthwhile and makes sense, and I look around the room and even the men are wiping th
eir eyes because this story about kinship, separation and \'85 Also, they don\rquote t know my history.  They don\rquote t know much about me, it\rquote s all absolutely brand new.
