\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 So I think that
\rquote s forming, and within a month or two, I\rquote m sitting with Raymond Firth and saying, \'93Would it be a bad idea to try and do research in a village where your father had emigrated from?\'94  And not
 realising that this was both a very simple and na\'efve question, and one absolutely freighted with all kinds of interesting resonances.  And Raymond, in my memory he looked at me, and his eye kind of twinkled a bit, and he didn\rquote 
t go into any of the complexities, and he simply said, \'93If you have a strong card in your hand, a strong suit in your hand, you should lead on it\'94.  So he gave me complete ethical professional permission to work in my father\rquote 
s village, which cleared away a major area of doubt, because if you think that you\rquote re getting into a social science, and all you know about science is the objectivism stories and neutrality, impartiality, control, if you\rquote 
ve picked up that stuff from reading about medicine and psychiatry, and there\rquote s all sorts of stuff in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 Street Corner Society}{
