\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 
Well Raymond would have three colours of ink, and he\rquote d be making notes throughout a seminar, in different coloured inks.  I don\rquote 
t think we ever quite found out what those inks meant. And then when it came to the dialogue part of the seminar, he would go around all the graduate students in the room, inviting them to contribute on a particular point, so he would raise a point out of
 the seminar, and say, \'93What Miss So and So said about Africa, is extremely interesting.  What do you think about it, Mr. Loizos?\'94  And you were expected to say something useful at that point, and you couldn\rquote t pass twice.  You might say, \'93
I don\rquote t think I want to comment at this point\'94, but this was definitely to lose face, and when he came round again, you\rquote 
d bloody better be ready!  So that was a didactic kind of seminar.  And then Raymond would sum up the discussion.  Maurice Bloch said that when he summed up, it was always completely misrepresenting what the discussion had been!  But that\rquote 
s just Maurice knocking the ancestors.  I think Raymond was extremely good at summing up.  You came out of it feeling that you had been made to see a set of issues arising out of a seminar paper, so this wasn\rquote 
t a hit or miss affair, it was something that illuminated you.  That was hard work, and a kind of gift.
