s lectures on kinship, which were, again, brilliant, but he was talking about Levi-Strauss and complex models, and I was pretty sure nothing in Cyprus was going to fit that agenda.  So the people I was being taught by weren\rquote 
t feeding directly into my perceptions of what was worth doing.  My supervisor, whom I loved to bits, and became a good friend, was a Melanesianist, and he knew little about the Med., and was a laid back character who preferred to have a drink with you 
than to read and comment on anything you\rquote d written. He\rquote d get round to that with some bit of prodding, he was all right on weekly essays, but when it came to thesis chapters, he could sit on them for six months.
