 I doing each day?  All right.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 My first experience of being in the village, in winter, is agoraphobia, in the sense that, in winter, there
\rquote s only two places to be \endash  there\rquote s in your house, keeping as warm as you can, they have no heating system to 
speak of, they might have paraffin stoves - thick sweaters is their heating system.  And in the coffee shop, where they do have heaters of various kinds, in the coffee shop, during the day in winter, there\rquote 
ll be a lot of men sort of smoking, playing cards,
 reading the paper, and conversing.  When I turn up in the coffee shop, not speaking very much Cypriot Greek, still an absolute beginner, you know, I have many cousins unknown to me.  I have 80 second cousins!  All right.  And so people come up to me and 
say, \'93Who am I?\'94  (LAUGHS)  \'93I am your cousin so and so. Remember it!\'94  Right.  Well, that\rquote s an easy sentence. But remembering them - they all look the same at first \endash  and it\rquote 
s quite difficult, and a lot of them are going to have the same name, because the Greek kinship system reproduces names down generations.  A lot of people called Andreas, and a lot of people called Yannis, and so on.  They\rquote 
ve also got nicknames, haven\rquote t they!  Some of them public nicknames, some of them private nicknames behind their backs and so on, but the other thing is, they all talk to me at once!  So it\rquote s bad enough when you don\rquote 
t know a language well, being with people one at a time, but when three of them are all talking to you at once, and nobody thinks that anybody else\rquote s conversation should take precedence, so there\rquote 
s three of them trying to talk at once, and I found it totally exhausting and deeply frustrating, and I knew I wasn\rquote t getting anything worth getting, I was just existing, I was struggling with the language.  So the 
effect of visiting the coffee shop was deep}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11154904\charrsid14965953 ly discouraging, demoralising.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 I hadn\rquote t managed to get the warm sweaters yet, I\rquote d contracted with a village lady who knitted, to knit me one, but I didn\rquote 
t realise I was supposed to give her the money up front to buy the wool, so it took a few weeks before we sorted that out!  Shivering, wearing everything I\rquote 
d got!  So I started staying indoors and feeling terrible and depressed, and unable to pursue my fieldwork, and that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5650543\charrsid14965953 
I was letting everybody down.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 The breakthrough was to realise that if I went to the coffee shop where the old men were \endash 
 in the centre of the village there\rquote s coffee shops with lots of younger, middle-aged, active people \endash  there\rquote s some per
ipheral coffee shops with very old men, who just go in there very quietly and sit all day over a coffee and read the newspaper.  These old guys were in their own world, and they were perfectly happy to do rough life history interviews, as it were, very ro
ugh, and that they would answer me in really simple Greek, because my questions would be simple, and their answers were often simple, and things would go slowly, and they would talk to me one at a time, and there wouldn\rquote 
t be all these guys playing games. So for weeks I went to the coffee shop where the old men were and interviewed them one by one, and built up semi-genealogy life history things. I did who their families were, where they\rquote d worked, what they\rquote 
d done, how much land they had, I built up little histories like that. But all the time my Greek was racing along, and every now and then they\rquote d use a word I didn\rquote t know, and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5515437\charrsid14965953 I\rquote d find it out and look it up.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 So after some weeks of that, I
\rquote d exhausted the number of old men I could find, and felt ready to try and re-engage a bit more with younger men, and I decided, just to feel that I was in control of something, I would do a mini survey on produce marketing \endash 
 I knew that people grew potatoes, carrots, beetroots, and two or three other things as well as citrus \endash 
 and I found out that farmers had extremely good memories about what price they got for which product over a series of years. So I could sit with a guy and say, \'93How much did you get for your potatoes in \rquote 65?\'94 and he\rquote 
d work it out and tell me, and then we\rquote d do five years of that, and these were things people were very happy to talk about.  Farmers love talking about those kinds of things.  So I did that for 10 or 15 people. 
