\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 
Oh, they were being enrolled in the Turkish Cypriot Defence Forces, preparing for their own State if Turkey ever came and turned the key in the door.  There\rquote s a lot to understand.  Between \rquote 64 and \rquote 
74, the Turkish Cypriots lived in 25 defended enclaves, it\rquote s a bit like what the Israelis want for the Palestinians.  They don\rquote t add up to a State, because they\rquote re fragments.  What happened in \rquote 
74 is the Turkish Army arrived, drove Greeks out of enough territory, the Turkish Cypriots now have a compact State, they will never let it go.  That\rquote s what happened.  But when I\rquote m there, they\rquote 
re still in the enclaves, so young men who are most at risk in inter-communal violence, were disappearing and getting into the Turkish enclaves and joining the Turkish Defence Forces.  That left old men and women in the village, and a few children.  
Plainly I didn\rquote t see the significance of that at the time.  I didn\rquote t know where it was going.  I didn\rquote t realise, in \rquote 74, it would all be - I bought property in Kyrenia, for God\rquote s sake!  I mean, how daft is that!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 I\rquote 
ve just got two last questions on the Greek bit.  One was, you obviously were able very easily to talk to the men, but how did you manage with the women?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid2108029 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Peter:\tab }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 Well, I had a fair number of female relatives who were warmly disposed to me. Some were my cousins, and some were married to my c
ousins, but especially the younger ones, I could talk to about anything, and one or two of my old aunts I could talk to about anything. So questions which, if I\rquote 
d asked them to an unrelated woman, would have been considered crossing embarrassing gender lines, I could ask within my kinship circle, and deal with any mild embarrassment. But I didn\rquote 
t pursue the kind of fine tuning of sexuality and things that would create gender embarrassment.  I picked stuff up by osmosis and by overhearing stuff.  A lot of thi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1914580\charrsid14965953 ngs are said and done in joke.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 I\rquote 
ll give you one example.  All right?  My cousin Tomas is going to go off on a Communist Party agricultural delegation to somewhere, and he\rquote s going through Athens, and he may be going to Russia \endash  I can\rquote t remember - Bulgari
a, wherever.  There was this stuff going on as well \endash the Cold War stuff.  Russians turned up in our village on an agricultural mission!  Ah!  (LAUGHS)  Okay!  So he\rquote s getting ready to go to the airport, and he\rquote 
s standing around with his wife, and they\rquote re about to separate, and she makes a joke!  Somebody says, \'93Maybe, you know, who knows what foreign women he\rquote ll meet when he\rquote s abroad\'94, and she says, \'93If I had my way, I\rquote 
d cut it off and keep i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1914580\charrsid14965953 t here!\'94  All right?  (LAUGHS) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 Well, you hear a thing like that, everybody laughs, and you think to yourself, \'93Honour and shame?  Come on, guys!\'94  You know!  There\rquote 
s another level in which these people interact and talk about these things, which isn\rquote t in Campbell, and it isn\rquote t in Friedl.  There\rquote s an earthiness and a dire
ctness there, and probably, if I were an outsider anthropologist, they wouldn\rquote t have said it in front of me.  So you do get privileged access.  I\rquote 
d finished my fieldwork with a bunch of very in-depth qualitative interviews about conflicts, and I selected, I can\rquote 
t remember how many, 15 or 20 [in fact 25] of my most articulate and relaxed informants, and went through everything I could think of about quarrels, conflicts, anything that figured in their lives as a dispute, because at the time I was inter}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2108029\charrsid14965953 ested in all that micro stuff.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 
I picked up stuff that way too. I mean, Tomas had had a row with another man, and they\rquote d exchanged insults in public in the coffee shop, and Tomas had said to him, \'93Don\rquote t think because I don\rquote t run after the daughter of Alpha and Vi
ta, that my cock doesn\rquote t stand up\'94.  And I remember saying to Tomas, one of my cousins \endash  scrub the reference to cousins \endash  somebody said to me, he\rquote d been abroad,  - no, I think we\rquote 
d better leave this stuff out, they would hate it if I said it!  
