\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 
Oh yes.  The Greeks left the wooden horse outside Troy, and inside it were the armed men who would get inside the city and destroy it.  So a Greek gift, to me, is an ambiguous gift, and that the gift of modern politics in the village is a Greek gift, 
because it is going to unleash the forces of institutional conflict.  Yeah.  That\rquote s what it\rquote 
s about.  Were they better off with modern politics or without them?  I say, somewhere in the book that, before modern politics, people fought about things they und
erstood like land boundaries and honour, but after modern politics they fight about ideas and things that take place in different cities around the world, without fully understanding them, so they\rquote re caught up in other people\rquote 
s games.  I think that\rquote s what I felt about them.
\par 
