\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid4291077 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10226308\charrsid14965953 Peter:\tab }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 
At some point late in 1969, I think, I met a fellow anthropologist, by accident, at dinner at the RAI, called Caroline Ifeka, her maiden name was Moller, but she had married a Mr. Ifek
a from Onisha, in Nigeria. An Ibo heartland town.  We met, we started seeing each other, we shared a house in Highgate for a while. She came to Cyprus a couple of times while I was writing my Ph.D.. I\rquote 
d bought a house in Cyprus, in Kyrenia, a village house
, because during my fieldwork I became obsessed with two sorts of things that arose out of my contact with my informants, some of whom were relatives, and one was that I was a man who owned nothing.  Yes.  And I came, on my mother\rquote 
s side, from a family who\rquote d never owned anything, that I know of.  I think they\rquote d only ever rented.  I have a question about whether my mother\rquote 
s father had bought a house in Lowther Hill, Peckham, or whether it was rented, and I know no way of finding that out, but certainly my mother never owned anything, and nor did any of her brothers and sisters.  I think there\rquote 
s a hard line there between the people in Britain who aspire and succeed to home ownership and those who don\rquote t.  So, the course of fieldwork, I mean, everybody in a Cypriot village owns something, even if it\rquote 
s only the house they live in, and there\rquote s a fantastic interest in land ownership.  The second thing was, I was thirty-something - one or two, and I was no longer married, and I didn\rquote t have any children, and everybody
 around me of my age was married and with children. So I think I got back to London feeling that there was something about the way I lived in England that was less successful and less effective, as a human being, than the people I\rquote 
d been studying.  I felt they\rquote 
d got their priorities right, getting hold of the piece of land and having a house on it, and having a wife and children, these were all very positive things. So I think, in that spirit, I went, fairly enthusiastically, into the relationship with Caro
line Ifeka. But it didn\rquote t last, due to my meeting and becoming very involved with the lady I\rquote m now married to.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10226308 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 
