t. It seemed to me that a man in my position would be totally inauthentic if he tried to pretend to be a Feminist, but the whole encounter with Caroline and Feminist Marxism and the lot obviously made me think a lot more about my own work and what I
\rquote d been doing. (LAUGHS) I was put in a very odd situation where I became editor of the journal of the Royal Anthropological Institute. I received a letter from Caroline Ifeka, effectively doing a re-analysis of an article I\rquote d published in }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 Man}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 , about property de
mography in Cyprus.  I mean, my first major work was done in collaboration with an LSE demographer called Chris Langford. It involved trying to marry up data from a particular village, patterns of villages for which I was responsible, with the analysis of
 the series of British Censuses for which Chris was responsible, and took two years playing squash with him to get him to look at the Cyprus Censuses, because he\rquote s a very thorough man and he doesn\rquote t do anything by halves, so he\rquote 
s either out and doesn\rquote t want to know, or he\rquote 
s in and goes all the way.  Anyway, I received a letter doing a kind of Marxist-Feminist re-analysis of my article, and I had to decide whether to publish this or not!  (LAUGHS)  I published it because, it seemed to me, to do anything else 
would be dishonourable, but I took advice from a very close friend \endash  John Davis, who was subsequently the Warden of All Souls, a fellow Mediterraneanist with whom I became very close \endash  and I said to John, \'93What do I do about this?\'94
  He said, \'93Nothing.  You do and say nothing.  You publish the article and leave it at that\'94, which was, of}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13200714\charrsid14965953 
 course, entirely good advice.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 
So after initial difficulties, Caroline decided to go off to the ANU with my former Ph.D. supervisor, Anthony Forge, who was a close friend of
 mine and a mentor, so she took her child and our child off to Australia, which was very very difficult for me, and, I think, for all of them, but it\rquote s what she did.  
