An Englishman invited me to his home, on a social visit, we were quite friendly at work, so he told me what time to come, and I arrived, and perhaps I was a little bit early\'94, he said, \'93
but his family were sitting around the table at four in the afternoon, eating beans on toast.  And he said, \lquote Sit down\rquote .  And he put me somewhere in another room, \lquote We\rquote ve nearly finished\rquote \'94.  And everybody said, \'93
And that was it?\'94  So they didn\rquote 
t feed him, is the point!  And people were fairly shocked at that, kind of gasped!  It seemed such a completely inhospitable thing to do.  If you cross a threshold in Cyprus for the first time, you must be given a p
iece of candied fruit and a glass of water, absolutely minimally a cup of coffee, whatever.  But if you arrived at a mealtime, you would have to sit and eat, or at least be asked to do so, and then r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3490024\charrsid14965953 efuse, and say, \'93I\rquote ve eaten\'94.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10034445\charrsid14965953 The other story, you see, 
he arrives in London, for the first time, with no English.  He\rquote s got an address written on a piece of paper, and he stops an Englishman in the street and shows him the piece of paper, and the man looks at it and shakes his head, and he says, \'93
Then this man, who\rquote s a complete stranger, took me on three buses and took me to the very house that I was looking for.  Where would you find a Cypriot who would do that for you?\'94
  So the British are sort of hopeless on food, but amazingly kind to strangers.  Now, what do you want to know about food?
