But what I wanted to do was a film in the so-called observational style, in which there is no commentary.  You film continuously in as many relevant contexts as you can, and you edit in such 
a way that the material speaks for itself. This is the dominant style that emerged from the British National Film and Television School in the late sixties/early seventies, and UCLA which had an ethnographic film programme, and the dominant brains in both
 of those programmes was the same man \endash  a Scot called Colin Young \endash 
 and the young film makers whom he trained, and who worked with him, including the most distinguished is David MacDougall. So there was a filming style that emerged, and it was only possible
 because, in 1960, there was a technical breakthrough in film equipment such that you could record synchronous sound simultaneously with the picture, by a one or two-man crew, instead of the very heavy equipment, studio equipment, that they\rquote 
d used before. So filming changed.  And my first film is pre-1960, technically and conceptually, and the second film is a not very successful attempt to get into the observational mainstream \endash  so you\rquote ll notice there is no commentary, there
\rquote s a few inter-titles, and there are several time zones.  And I think the film is not - I edited it myself \endash  I don\rquote t think I\rquote m a masterly editor of my own material!  I could probably edit someone else\rquote 
s material, but I needed an editor, and I made a decision to edit it.
